              <h2 style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Linux
                  Distributions</span></h2>
              <span style="font-family: Arial,Sans-Serif;">Linux is an operating
                system designed to be very close to UNIX but as a free open
                source distribution.  </span><span style="font-family: Arial,Sans-Serif;"><span
                  style="font-family: Arial,Sans-Serif;">Linux in most cases is
                  free of charge as it is open source and tends to be more
                  secure then Windows. </span>It comes in many </span>flavors
              the main difference is the tools used for administration and
              instillation. All distributions are based on GNU tools and the
              Linux Kernel.  Most of the servers on the internet run Linux.  <br />
              <br />
              The most common distributions are Red Hat, Debian and SUSE. 
              Everyone has an opinion as to what the best distribution is I have
              gone over some of the most popular here.  All the mainstream
              distributions of Linux are great and have their own advantages,
              you can check them out at <a href="http://www.linux.org">Linux.org</a>.<br />
              <p><a href="http://www.redhat.com/"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Redhat</span></a>
                Enterprise is the most common Linux used commercially as it is
                easy to install and manage, as well as having support from
                Redhat.  <a href="http://www.centos.org/">CentOs</a> is the
                same as Red Hat Enterprise expect for the name and not having
                Redhat support.  The binary's are the same as it is built from
                the same distribution as Red Hat Enterprise and it is Free<span
                  style="font-weight: bold;">.  </span>Redhat also has a free
                version called <a href="getfedora.org">Fedora</a> witch is
                great but not exactly the same as Redhat's enterprise version. 
                This server is running CentOS on VMware ESXi.</p>
              <p><a href="www.debian.org"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Debian</span></a>
                is also a very common version of Linux and many commercial
                servers are running it.  In the past it was a little harder to
                install but the newer versions are easy to install.  <a href="http://www.ubuntu.com/">Ubuntu</a>
                is also a very popular Linux version that is based on the Debian
                distribution. </p>
              <p><a href="http://en.opensuse.org"><span style="font-weight: bold;">SuSe</span></a>
                is the another very popular Linux distribution and is worth
                checking out. </p>
              <p><a href="http://www.freebsd.org"><span style="font-weight: bold;">FreeBSD</span></a>
                while not Linux is a very popular open source version of UNIX.
                It is derived from BSD (Berkeley Software Distribution), the
                version of UNIX developed at Berkeley.  FreeBSD in some cases is
                much closer to UNIX then Linux as the original code was based on
                AT&amp;Ts UNIX.  It is used on many Internet servers and
                appliances. You can download and try FreeBSD at <a href="http://www.freebsd.org">FreeBSD.org</a></p>
              <p><a style="font-weight: bold;" title="cygwin" href="https://www.cygwin.com/">cygwin</a>
                is not Linux but is a port of many of the Linux tools for
                windows.  I love cygwin as it allows me to have access to most
                of the GNU tools in windows.  For the most part it gives you a
                Linux shell on windows.  </p>
